text: hi everyone
Anthony Fantana here the Internet's
busiest music nerd and it's time for
your review of the new havoc album
unnatural selection havoc is a Denver
Colorado thrash metal outfit this is
their third full-length LP if you
remember I loved their previous
full-length album time's up one of my
favorite metal albums of 2011 on that LP
they took a ton of influence from bands
such as Megadeth who I think they sort
of borrow from the most overkill and
anthrax too and they really took to
copying these these very old-school
thrash metal vibes with a lot of passion
and gusto and making them translate
pretty well to this very modern beefy
production sound now the production
quality from their debut LP two times up
I mean it was a pretty nice transition
enough to make times up a worthwhile
change in sort of a peak in their career
however there is just not as much
daylight between a natural selection and
times up sonically or stylistically I
mean the production is roughly the same
the gang vocals are still there the
solos are in roughly the same style the
riffs as well maybe the drum sounds have
changed a little bit going for more of
that kind of very punchy plastic e sound
that a lot of modern metal bands really
enjoy having in their songs the vocals
are definitely a little more over the
top which can be a bit of a double-edged
sword I think it can make this album
more memorable for some people but it's
to the point where they can become a
little too much maybe corny some of the
singing that the vocals attempt can be
somewhat off as opposed to the gruff
somewhat high-pitched shouting that goes
into a havoc album that is very early
Dave Mustaine esque and the lyrics
definitely take a much more political
tone on this record too
government is spying on us don't tread
on me kind of thing which is actually
pretty relevant for this time there were
socially aware lyrics on their last full
length but they had more of an
apocalyptic theme on them a lot of war
imagery too and there are some other
topics covered as well like on the song
waste of life honestly
natural selection really does feel in a
big way like a sequel a direct sequel to
time is up except maybe a little less
catchy I do think that there are songs
on here that havoc is not writing them
with as much pomp but I I think
shot-for-shot this album is every bit as
good as time's up the issue for me
personally though is just that it's a
little stale to me what havoc is trying
to do on this record which essentially
is just a Xerox of their previous record
and you know I do realize that they are
kind of chasing after a style that's
kind of their thing but the very meat
and potatoes approach that they took to
playing thrash metal was sort of made up
for by how catchy their last LP was with
this one just not being up to snuff in
that regard and the band kind of
hammering through this blueprint as
opposed to sort of building on it or
trying some new things with it it makes
a natural selection kind of a
forgettable listen even if some of the
grooves that the riffs pump out are
pretty good basically that's my take on
the album overall if you've given this
thing a listen what did you think of it
did you love it did you hate it why what
do you think I should review next and
